<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Blames Israel for Peace Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today insisted that
Israel is to blame for the stalemate on all tracks of the
Arab-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Jordan's Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali affirmed that it would clarify its points of view to
visiting United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her maiden trip to the region since taking office
earlier this year, is expected to arrive here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Majali blamed Israel for the current overall deadlock of the
peace process and said that Jordan would make it known to Albright
during her trip, which he described as "important," Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's position was in complete harmony with that of Egypt,
added Majali, who signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 making
Jordan the second Arab country after Egypt to conceive peace with
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel did not live up to its promises and in effect pushed the
peace process into a serious logjam, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
All the parties concerned with the peace process should work
for the full implementation of all signed agreements as well as
fulfillment of promises about the future of peace, he added.
</P>
<P>
They all should work in the same direction until realizing a
comprehensive and lasting peace in this part of the world, he
emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
