<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton Saturday once again called for overhauling the laws on
political contributions.
</P>
<P>
"I'm doing what I can within the executive branch," he said in
his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
He cited concrete action on reform, such as asking the Federal
Communications Commission to require free broadcast time for
candidates and requesting the Federal Election Commission to ban
unlimited contributions to political parties by businessmen,
unions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
"But there is no substitute for strong, bipartisan campaign
finance reform legislation passed by the Congress," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He added that while he had backed such bills every year since
he took office, efforts were blocked by filibusters in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Clinton criticized "the opponents of reform" for gearing up to
keep legislation from coming to a vote at all.
</P>
<P>
"Let's be clear -- a vote to filibuster campaign reform is a
vote to keep special interest money and kill reform. A vote to
filibuster is a vote for the status quo," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, in a brief
interview, said he might consider revamping campaign finance laws
even before the completion of hearings on political fund-raising
abuses in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Lott had said that before the full Senate considers
changing the laws, he wants to wait for the end of hearings on
fund raising by the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee so that
lawmakers would know if current laws were broken.
</P>
<P>
But Lott said Friday, "I don't know if that will be essential."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, he said such a plan should include a
Republican-sought provision, which would make it harder for unions
to use members' dues for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Democrats have pressured Republican
congressional leaders to schedule votes on a bipartisan measure,
the McCain-Feingold plan that would ban so-called soft money --
unlimited funds raised for party-wide activities like voter
turnout efforts.
</P>
<P>
It would also restrict donations by political action committees
and offer free or reduced-cost television advertising time to
candidates who voluntarily limit spending.
</P>
<P>
Plans to overhaul campaign finance laws have been obstructed
for years in Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
