<HEADLINE> Tianjin Witnesses Rapid Social and Economic Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of photographs,
models and products illustrating the rapid growth of Tianjin
municipality, an old industrial and commercial center in north
China, are on display in an ongoing one-month national exhibit.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin is just one of the 30-odd province-level areas
represented at the show in the Beijing Exhibition Center, themed
"A Glorious Five Years -- An Exhibition on Achievements Made in
Economic Development and Social Ethical and Cultural Progress
since the 14th CPC National Congress held in 1992."
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Tianjin municipality has regained its
vigor as an industrial base, witnessing a double-digit increase in
the gross domestic product for five consecutive years, while
keeping its price level low among the country's 35 large and
medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the municipality has pulled 65 percent of
its state-owned enterprises out of financial difficulty and helped
700,000 laid-off workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Sixty of the world's 100 top trans-national companies have
invested in the Binhai New Area, a hi-tech and export-oriented
modern economic zone,
</P>
<P>
The city has demolished 3.98 million sq.m. of run-down houses,
and built 10.05 sq.m. of housing since 1994, directly benefiting
500,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tianjin has also witnessed remarkable ethical and
cultural progress over the past five years. Its Heping District
has been set as a model by the State.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the port city has successfully hosted the 43rd
World Table Tennis Championship and China's first Beijing Opera
Festival and will host the 1999 World Gymnastics Championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
