<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Daohan on Relations With Taiwan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The part dealing with
promoting peaceful reunification of the motherland in Jiang
Zemin's report made at the on-going 15th Party Congress is
explicit and has a big leeway, Wang Daohan, president of the
Association of Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang appealed, in his report, that the two sides of the
Straits can, as the first step, hold negotiations and reach an
agreement on officially ending the state of hostility between the
two sides in accordance with the principle that there is only one
China, Wang said this afternoon at a discussion attended by
delegates from Shanghai, China's largest industrial center.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also stated that on this basis the two sides can
undertake jointly to safeguard China's sovereignty and territorial
integrity and work out plans for the future growth of their
relations, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
With the return of Hong Kong to the embrace of the motherland,
Wang said, China is confronted with the reunification between the
both sides of the Taiwan Straits, which is a complicated matter
owning to the interference of foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
But Jiang Zemin clearly stated in his report that China is to
achieve the reunification of motherland by peaceful means under
the condition that Taiwan will not seek independence, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
The reunification of the two sides of the Taiwan Straits is
China's internal affair and the people living on both sides are
Chinese, Wang said. "Hence, we should sit together for
negotiations," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Daohan on Relations With Taiwan (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang said that Jiang's second point was the Chinese Communist
Party places hopes not only on the Taiwan authorities, but also on
the various circles there. If any political party wants to send a
delegation over to exchange views, they are welcome, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the CPC also places hopes on the people of
Taiwan. It is necessary, he said, to help them understand that the
eventual reunification will not affect adversely their interests.
Cooperation between the two sides of the Straits will noly benefit
them with even better opportunities for development, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that some compatriots there were worried whether the
mainland would move against Taiwan militarily. "We have stated
repeatedly that the military exercises held last year were not
directed at the people of Taiwan," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of "Taiwan independence," he said, "we will
adopt peaceful means to realize the reunificaiton of the
motherland. We have the patience and determination, and therefore
confidence. The overwhelming majority of the nations in the world
recognize that Taiwan is part of Chian and there is only one
China. This is norms of the international order." 
</P>
</TEXT>
