<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders to Discuss Angolan Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) will meet at the end of this
month in Luanda to bring Angola's peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced today by SADC executive secretary
Kaire Mbuende in Gaborone, Botswana, the Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of SADC's 14 member states will discuss the conflict
between the Angolan government and the former rebel movement, the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Mbuende said lack of committment by UNITA to take part fully
in the government of national unity and failure to demobilise its
troops remain a cause of concern.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, which fought 20 years of civil war against the ruling
MPLA party, is part of the government of national unity. But its
leader, Jonas Savimbi, refused to travel to Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council threatens to impose
sanctions against UNITA, unless it complies with the 1994 peace
protocol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
