<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Invest Heavily in SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Investment
Bank (EIB), the main financing institution of the European Union,
is prepared to provide more finance to technology-related and
high-growth small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
Sir Brian Unwin, head of the bank, told an informal meeting of
the EU finance ministers today that the Amsterdam Special Action
Program, formulated after the Amsterdam Treaty was signed in June
this year, was to become a new instrument to help finance SMEs.
</P>
<P>
The SMEs to get EIB financing are those most likely to expand,
remain competitive and create new and stable jobs as defined by
Unwin.
</P>
<P>
Yet the creation or development of such companies is often
hindered through unavailability of adequate capital funds, Unwin
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank is also discussing with the European Investment Fund
(EIF) the creation of a new European Technology Facility, with
funding from bank's surplus, to provide venture capital to SMEs in
the high-tech field.
</P>
<P>
The European Technology Facility is expected to gather up to
125 million ECUs of EIB funds for small and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Unwin described technology related and high-growth SMEs as
capable of benefiting in future from risk-sharing or subordinated
loans as well as equity and venture capitals provided by the EIB
and EIF through other sound financial intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
The EIF is another major financing arm of the 15-nation union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
