<HEADLINE> Iraq Allows Overseas Iranians to Visit Shiite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein has issued an instruction allowing the overseas Iranians
to visit Shiite Muslim holy shrines in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi News Agency reported today that the Interior Ministry and
other concerned government organs have been instructed to lift a
ban on the entry of Iranian passport holders who live outside Iran.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Iran brushed off an Iraqi decision to, for
the first time in 17 years, allow Iranian pilgrims to pay homage
to Shiite Mulism holy shrines in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government demanded that talks be held with the
Iraqi side to prepare for the visits of Iranian citizens but
the Iraqi government rejected the request.
</P>
<P>
Shiites and Sunnis are the two major factions of Islam. Iran is
the only Shiite Muslim-dominated country in the region and the
most important Shiite shrines are in neighboring rival - Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has decided that the Iranian expatriates
can come to Iraq through the Qadesia checkpoint on the
Iraqi-Jordanian border and El-Walid checkpoint on the Iraqi-Syrian
border.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians are permitted to stay no more than seven days (six
nights that can not be renewed or extended), and required to
maintain public order and respect laws and rules during their stay.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi tourism authority and Al-Hoda Company for Religions
Tourism have provided all the necessary means to transport the
Iranian visitors coming in batches or families, according to INA.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought an eight-year war from 1980-88 and are
still at odds with each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
