<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Sensitized to Killer Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's education, sports
and culture deputy minister Kembo Mohadi today said there is need
to raise awareness in schools and communities about the killer
cancer disease.
</P>
<P>
Addressing people gathered to commemorate the Terry Fox
nine-kilometre fun run at the University of Zimbabwe in Harare,
Mohadi said sports should be used to raise cancer awareness
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"Physical education, sport and recreation provide meaningful
stimulating experience that enhances self-esteem of youths and
also provides them with opportunities to develop attitudes and
values, knowledge and physical skills which help to take care of
themselves and others in need of caring in the communities," said
Mohadi.
</P>
<P>
Harare Hospital superintendent Mohamed Ali, representing
health and child welfare minister Timothy Stamps said cancer
could be prevented if detected early.
</P>
<P>
He said a third of the cancer patients diagnosed in Zimbabwe
could prevent the disease with a change in lifestyle, such as
eating habits, drinking, smoking including sleeping.
</P>
<P>
Ali said another third of the cancer patients disgonised with
proper therapy could somehow be cured while another third
diagonised late could not be saved.
</P>
<P>
"We hope and encourage young people to follow lifestyle and
habits that prevent cancer," he said.
</P>
<P>
A young unfortunate cancer victim, Terry Fox started the race
in Canada. He lost a leg to cancer and had a dream that he would
raise from every Canadian a dollar by running on one leg.
</P>
<P>
Fox started in 1980 and managed to run about 26 miles per day
for 143 days before dying of cancer, now the event is a worldwide
event to raise awareness about cancer and funds for research and
the cancer society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
