<HEADLINE> Iran Releases American Jailed for Illegal Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran today released a black
American citizen who was arrested in April 1996 on charge of
illegal entry to the country.
</P>
<P>
This was announced was made by the Iranian Judiciary, which
said the freed U.S. citizen, Joseph Morris, was serving a sentence
of two years in prison for illegally entering Iran from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"He would soon be deported from the country," said the
Judiciary's public relations office.
</P>
<P>
However, a source who had contact with Morris said the American
has been in detention in an Iranian prison for 16 months, instead
of eight months as the Iranian judicial authorities had claimed.
</P>
<P>
The source said on condition of anonymity that Morris, 38, has
been in detention since April 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that the American, who hails from New Orleans,
Louisiana, lied about his position in the U.S. army reserves when
he took part in U.S.-led operation Desert Storm to drive Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein's forces out of Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"Morris told the Iranian authorities that he was an officer in
the army reserve whereas he was only a private first class and a
desk jockey, not a foot soldier," the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
