<HEADLINE> Opposition Blames Kabila for Blocking UN Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A rival opposition has
accused President Laurent Kabila of Democratic Republic of Congo
of preventing a United Nations task team investigating human
rights atrocities in his country.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Union for Democracy and Social Progress, Mutombo
Kabundji, said in a statement issued here today that the UN team
was still bogged down in Kinshasa because the government "refused
to allow it to start its mission".
</P>
<P>
Kabundji said major compromises had been made to accommodate
Kabila's complaints following the appointment of the team.
</P>
<P>
It said one of the region's top experts had been dropped from
the team and the UN had acceded to Kabila's demand to extend the
inquiry beyond 1996.
</P>
<P>
This means the team cannot concentrate only on atrocities
which occurred in the latest seven-month war that left thousands
dead and millions displaced, claimed Kabundji.
</P>
<P>
He said he was convinced that Kabila's latest demands were
"clear signs that they are determined to block the UN inquiry
commission from getting the facts".
</P>
<P>
He called on South Africa to press Congo (K) into cooperation
fully with the UN team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
