<HEADLINE> Zambia Denies Provatizing Broadcasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia said here today that
it will not privatize at least in the near future the state-owned
Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation (ZNBC).
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Ronald Penza told a television program that
the government's immediate concern is making ZNBC more efficient.
</P>
<P>
What matters to the government is whether or not the
broadcasting corporation is achieving the goals for which it was
established, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's concern is to ensure that the
corporation, which also includes the television, informs,
educates and entertains the Zambians.
</P>
<P>
Penza said that governments even in liberal democracies own
media organizations to achieve non-commercial goals such as
public information and education.
</P>
<P>
From the remarks, it is clear that the Zambian government
intends ZNBC to provide a social service rather a commercial one.
</P>
</TEXT>
