<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Youths Urged to be Responsible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Health and Child Welfare
Minister Timothy Stamps said Zimbabwean youths deserve special
attention in order to prepare them to be responsible future
leaders and parents.
</P>
<P>
Officially launching a six-month youth responsibility campaign
project in Mutare, east Zimbabwe Saturday, Stamps said young
people faced many challenges in their lives, forcing them into
alcohol abuse and early sexual activities.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of youth responsibility pilot projects was also
launched in two provinces. The projects seek to promote
responsible behavior among the youth in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
For the next six months, trained youth peer groups will be
visiting schools and youth centers to promote the concept of
behaving responsibly in order to fight HIV and sexually
transmitted infections.
</P>
<P>
Stamps said half of the young men aged 15 to 24 and a quarter
of the girls in the same age group were sexually active, exposing
themselves to the dangers of sexually transmitted infections and
unplanned pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
In the past 12 months, 408 children under the age of 14 were
treated for sexually transmitted diseases in Mutare while 172
youths were arrested for various criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
Executive director of Zimbabwe National Family Planning
Council Alex Zinanga said youths were the hope for the future and
they needed to be moulded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
