<HEADLINE> Albright Arrives in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright arrived in Saudi Red Sea coastal city of Jeddah
today on the fifth leg of her Middle East tour aimed at reviving
the dying peace process.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reported from Jeddah that Albright
would hold talks later with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz on the
peace process and regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
She would also meet with foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states who postponed their scheduled
meeting in Saudi Arabia by one day to talks with Albright in the
southern Saudi town of Abha.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to brief the Saudi leadership on the
outcome of her visit to Israel, Palestine, Syria and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in Cairo, Albright renewed a call to the Israelis and
Palestinians to live up to their commitments regarding the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Kuna said that the Saudi leaders would voice deep concern to
the secretary over the adverse developments in the process due to
Israel's obstinate stances and diversion from peace spirit and
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright's discussions with the GCC foreign
ministers are believed to focus on limiting the threatened boycott
of the fourth Middle East and North African economic summit
scheduled for mid-November in Doha, Qatar, which Israel will be
invited to attend.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Oman, Bahrain,
Qatar, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Syria and Lebanon have already
announced to boycott the summit if Israel participates. Most of
the other Arab countries adopt a wait-and-see stance and stand by
an Arab League foreign ministers' meeting in Cairo on September
20-21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
