<HEADLINE> World Gold Price Under Downward Pressure: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) - In spite of a record level of
physical demand, the gold price remained under constant downward
pressure through most of the first half of 1997, according to a
report released today by Gold Fields Mineral Services Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The London-based research company said this was due to an
equally dramatic increase in supply emanating from central bank
sales, producer hedging and short selling from funds and other
speculators, chiefly in North America.
</P>
<P>
All the major components of physical demand rose strongly
year-on-year in the first half, with both jewellery and
electronics fabrication reaching new record levels.
</P>
<P>
World jewellery fabrication rose year-on-year by 16% to 1,592
tons in the first half of 1997, comfortably exceeding the
previous first half record of 1,397 tons set in 1995. Total
fabrication also rose to a new record level of 1,857 tons.
</P>
<P>
This was accompanied by a robust recovery in bar hoarding to
167 tons, although some way behind the recent high of 172 tons set
in the first half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
On the supply side, the report said, in spite of the 12%
year-on year decline in the average dollar gold price in the
first half, mine production continued to increase, though by a
marginal 1.4%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
