<HEADLINE> Moscow-Grozny Talks Begin in Dagomys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Talks on a treaty between
Moscow and the breakaway republic of Chechnya began today in
Dagomys, just outside Sochi on the Black Sea coast, according to
the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian security chief Ivan Rybkin during the talks once again
demanded that Chechnya correct the statement issued by
Vice-President Vakha Arsanov against Russian leadership before the
beginning of the talks.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "whenever a high official in Moscow permits
himself a roughly-worded statement on Chechnya, he is immediately
corrected by the President of Russia. Judging from all
appearances, there is no one in Chechnya to correct Vice-President
Vakha Arsanov."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the transit of early Caspian oil via Chechen
territory, Rubkin said this question had been fully solved.
</P>
<P>
The talks were attended, on the Moscow side, by Security Council
secretary Ivan Rybkin, Vice-Premier of the Russian Federation
Ramazan Abdulatipov, State Duma leader Alexander Shokhin, Minister
for the Affairs of Nationalities and Federative Relations
Vyacheslav Mikhailov.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya was represented by First Vice-Premiers Movladi Udugov
and Akhmed Zakayev, YuNCO oil company chief Khoj-Akhmed
Yarikhanov and President Aslan Maskhadov's political adviser
Said-Hassan Abumuslimov.
</P>
<P>
The negotiating parties will set forth their respective
vision of a single legal, defense, military, economic, financial,
budgetary, currency and educational space, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the press office of the Russian Security Council,
special attention of the talks will be given to human and civil
rights and freedoms and to interaction between the law-enforcement
agencies of the Russian Federation and Chechnya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
