<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Albright's Visit to Damascus Makes No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The talks between Syrian
President Hafez Al-Assad and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright here last night failed to make any substantial progress
except a verbal agreement on continuing contacts.
</P>
<P>
Soon after their talks, a spokesman for the Syrian presidency
said the two sides agreed on the continuation of contacts with a
view to establish peace between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit to Syria was part of her shuttle diplomacy in
the Middle East in an attempt to revive the dying peace process.
She was scheduled to visit Israel, the Palestinian self-rule
areas, Syria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Al-Assad and Albright reviewed the efforts
to resume peace negotiations on all tracks and positions of the
concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad reiterated his country's keenness on establishing a
just and comprehensive peace in the region on the basis of the
Madrid peace conference, the relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions and the land-for-peace formula.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the necessity of resuming the talks from where
they were left off and without pre-conditions.
</P>
<P>
Albright was briefed on the Syrian viewpoints on the peace
process and the extent of Syria's readiness for peace. However,
she did not bring Syria any new proposals from Israel to
facilitate a resumption of talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright's talks with the Syrian side failed, according to
diplomatic sources, to make a substantial progress on the Syrian
and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the U.S. secretary of state focused on security for
Israel and refrained from putting pressures on Israel, leaving the
substantial and delicate issues in the Arab-Israeli conflict
intact.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent Israeli government insists on the precedence of
Israeli security over peace and rejects withdrawal of its troops
from the Syrian Golan Heights it occupied since 1967.
</P>
<P>
Syria urged Netanyahu's government to to comply with the
land-for-peace principle, implement its pledge to pull out its
troops from the Golan, and resume the talks from the point they
had reached at.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit came as Syria and Israel trumpeted up media
threats as well as military buildup.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Syria of preparing for launching a chemical warfare,
Israel is massing up troops and conducting war games on the Golan
and escalating military confrontation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Unless the U.S. exerts pressure on Israel - its strategic ally
- and change its own unbalanced attitude, it seems impossible for
peace talks to resume and tensions in the region to defuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
