<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Pays Tribute to ECOWAS Liberian Peace Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) today paid tribute to west African
countries for the efforts in resolving the conflict in Liberia,
thus contributing to the sub-regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to say that ECOWAS (The Economic Community of West
African States) and ECOMOG (peace-keeping force of ECOWAS) have
been perfect in the situation of Liberia," said OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, quoted by the Nigerian
television authority.
</P>
<P>
Although mistakes were made, the ECOWAS member countries were
sincerely working for peace in Liberia when they sent the
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG to that country seven years
ago, according to Salim.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that this was a very genuine attempt to resolve
an internal conflict without any particular benefit to the
Nigerians, Ghanaians, etc," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no perceived national interest. There is the
perceived continental interest," he said, adding that this
indicated that "Africa is prepared to attempt to solve some
problems."
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS countries have been working closely in the attempt to
restore peace in Liberia. ECOMOG has successfully disarmed and
demobilized the warring factions, and ensured environment
favorable to the elections in July which led to the establishment
of a new government in that war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
At present ECOMOG is also involved in the sub-regional effort
to resolve the crisis in Sierra Leone, where the legitimate
government was ousted in a coup four months ago.
</P>
<P>
OAU has aired its support to the ECOWAS efforts. Observers
noted that Salim's remarks may serve as encouragement to ECOWAS'
embargo on Sierra Leone, which has been enforced as a means to
force the junta out of power.
</P>
<P>
The junta in power has claimed that the embargo is an
intervention into the country's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, B.A.T. Balewa, special envoy of Nigeria's head of
state general Sani Abacha, has described the ECOWAS success in
Liberia as providing a model and justification for regional
intervention in political crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It shows the feasibility of regional mechanisms in conflict
management and resolution" by applying the sub-region's own
resources, he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
