<HEADLINE> Tibetan Delegates Endorse Party's Basic Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Deng Xiaoping Theory is the
guarantee to improve reform, development and stability in areas
inhabited by ethnic minorities, delegates of the Tibetan
nationality said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 22 delegates from the Tibet Autonomous Region, in southwest
China, shared the view that the principle of paying equal
importance to cultural and ethical progress and material progress
put forward by Deng Xiaoping is a guideline in their work.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to have an all-round development in the
region if it is unstable," a delegate said.
</P>
<P>
The delegates agreed that the region should wage a resolute
struggle against splittist activities by the Dalai Lama and
safeguard the sovereignty and reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Raidi, chairman of the regional people's congress standing
committee, said the Party Central Committee has long been
attaching great importance to development in areas inhabited by
ethnic minorities and worked out a series of principles and
policies for development in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, Tibet has enjoyed unity between the army and the
people, rapid economic growth, brisk market and improved living
standards.
</P>
<P>
Gyaincain Norbu, chairman of the regional people's government,
said, "We should stick to the Party's basic line, take economic
development as the central task and develop the productive forces
in the entire primary stage of socialism.
</P>
<P>
Though Tibet has scored great achievements since the economic
reform started in 1978, there is still a big gap in the
development between Tibet and other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
"It is more important for us to persist in the Party's basic
line in Tibet," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lobang Toinzaub, the regional Party committee secretary, said
all the achievements made in the region, which has entered
socialism from a feudal serfdom, are the result of the guiding
ideology of seeking truth from facts set by Deng Xiaoping, central
government's policies for Tibetan development and support from the
people of all nationalities in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
