<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis Call for More Follow-up Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today
praised U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit to the
Middle East and called for more follow-up efforts to put the peace
process back on track.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal said to this
effect at a joint news conference with Albright in Saudi mountain
resort of Abha near the Yemen border, according to reports from
Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the news conference, Albright met with foreign
ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states, who
postponed their conference in Abha for a day in order to talk with
the U.S. secretary of state. GCC groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the
United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal said Albright's visit constituted a good opportunity
to discuss the current difficulties concerning the peace process,
to reiterate keenness on cooperation and the joint will to end the
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the visit came at a critical stage as Israel repeatedly
obstructed the peace process through its hardline policy and
"flagrant violations" of the principles of the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed Albright's support of the "land for peace"
principle and the United Nations Security Council resolutions 242
and 338, in addition of her criticism of Tel Aviv's "unilateral
measures" such as the construction of a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem which sparked off the current crisis and series of
violence.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that more concrete measures will be
taken to press the right-wing Israeli government to come back on
the track of the "land for peace" formula.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Albright said she agreed with her GCC
counterparts on confidence-building steps in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
She said the GCC foreign ministers encouraged her to continue
her efforts to end the current deadlock in the talks between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During her talks with the GCC ministers, Albright briefed them
on the outcome of her tour of Israel, the Palestinian self-rule
areas, Syria and Egypt in a bid to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright reiterated that "the Palestinian (National) Authority
must do everything within its power to prevent and punish
terrorism and to deepen the irrevocable commitment it made at Oslo
to treat Israel not as adversary but as partners in peace."
</P>
<P>
She also said "Israeli leaders must refrain from unilateral
actions that undermine Palestinian confidence in their intentions
and should bear in mind that no nation has a greater stake than
Israel in helping Palestinians to prosper."
</P>
<P>
She said that the U.S. will continue to meet the
responsibility to support peace in the region "by supporting a
comprehensive peace consistent with the principles outlined in
U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338, including the
land-for-peace" formula.
</P>
<P>
She called on Arab states to do their utmost to ensure that no
assistance of any kind reaches the extremists such as Hamas.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi foreign minister categorically denied at the press
conference that GCC states were extending support to the Islamic
Resistance Movement Hamas.
</P>
<P>
He saided that assistance was extended instead to the
Palestinian National Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
