<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ministers on Reform of State Sector of Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China has entered a critical
and final stage in the reform of state firms although the state
sector produced 2.2 percent more losses in the first half of this
year, said Wang Zhongyu, minister in charge of the State Economic
and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference this afternoon held for the
on-going 15th Party congress, Wang said the reason why many
state-owned enterprises are running in the red is that these
enterprises have lagged behind in operational ideas and many of
them are over-staffed and debt-ridden.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, about one third of China's schools
and hospitals are run by state firms, which means that the state
firms have to take care of their workers and their offsprings in
food, shelter and social services.
</P>
<P>
Wang made the above remarks with Chen Jinhua, minister in
charge of the State Planning Commission, and Zhang Haoruo,
vice-minister of the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economic Systems.
</P>
<P>
Wang said economic restructuring will benefit state-owned
enterprises in the long run but causes difficulties for them at
present for it takes time for these enterprises to adjust
themselves for the new changes.
</P>
<P>
Under the planned economic conditions, he said, enterprises can
sell their products and make profits if they have production
capacities. However, the situation has changed with the
transformation from the sellers' market to the buyers' market.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the internationalization of China's domestic market
with the influx of foreign investment and import products has
fueled market competition in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the difficult situation for the state firms is the
result of accumulation of difficulties in the traditional economic
structure. And reform has made these problems more conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
China aims to introduce the mechanism described as "the
survival of the fittest" by establishing the socialist market
economy. Even if the modern enterprise system has been established
in China, there still exist debt-ridden state enterprises, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
