<HEADLINE> Pakistan Expels 2 Indian Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Just one day before the
start of a new round foreign secretary level talks between
Pakistan and India, Pakistan has asked two Indian diplomats to
leave the country by Wednesday, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan government has declared the two officials with
Indian High Commission, identified as J.S. Bisid and V. Gobalan,
here as "persona non grata", accusing that they have done
activities incompatible for their status, the official souses
said.
</P>
<P>
India last night expelled two staffers with the Pakistan High
Commission in New Delhi on charges of spying.
</P>
<P>
The trade of expulsions of diplomats between Pakistan and India
took place just days before the commencement of a critical new
round bilateral talks between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has agreed to attend the third round of the
Pakistan-Indian foreign secretary level talks scheduled for
September 15 to 18 in New Delhi, a Foreign Office spokesman
announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary level talks
in March after a suspense of more than three years amidst signs of
improved relations between the two arch rivals in South Asia. The
Pakistan-Indian foreign secretary level talks have broken down in
1994 due to their serious differences over Jammu and Kashmir
disputes.
</P>
<P>
During last round of such talks held here in June, the two
sides have agreed to set up eight working groups to solve all the
outstanding issues including Kashmir and peace and security
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Since their independence in 1947, Pakistan and India have
fought three wars, two of which were over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
