<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Say Most Britons Back Changes to Monarchy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth's popularity
was believed to be at the lowest in her 45-year old reign as two
recent opinion polls found that most of the pollees support
changes to the British monarchy.
</P>
<P>
The royals have already suffered a dramatic drop in popularity
following the death of Princess Diana in a car crash in Paris two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
A poll for the Sunday Times conducted this week found more than
53 percent of the pollees want the queen to step down within the
next three years. The queen will be 75 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1073 people said today almost three in four
people (more than 70 percent) believe the queen is remote and out
of touch.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Labor MPs who responded to the survey want
the monarchy to be more open and accountable.
</P>
<P>
Another poll for the Observer suggests that 74 percent think
the monarchy should be modernized and should be more informal.
</P>
<P>
The royals came under attack from the media and the public in
the days following Diana's death. The queen in particular was
accused of aloofness for declining to appear in public and share
the nation's grief.
</P>
<P>
Her broadcast to the nation nine days ago, on the eve of
Diana's funeral, was seen as an futile attempt to reach out to the
people.
</P>
<P>
The two poll finding seemed to be the worst since the queen
inherited the throne in 1952.
</P>
<P>
A 1990 poll for the Sunday Times found that 47 percent of
people thought she should be prepared to step down in favour of
Prince Charles "at some stage", but this was understood to be a
question only for the long term.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Alderson, a political analyst said: "Today's findings
suggest the long term has arrived." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
