<HEADLINE> Israeli Public Sector Workers Stage Partial Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- About 150,000 public sector
workers in Israel staged partial strikes today following an
Israeli Trade Union decision to protest against the government
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
The strike paralyzed services provided by hospitals, courts,
Israeli Electric Company, National Insurance Institute and other
bodies for two hours.
</P>
<P>
About 1,700 workers in the Agriculture Ministry did not receive
the public, answer phone calls or process mail, nor did they issue
import or export permits or administer vaccinations to animals.
</P>
<P>
Stoppages by 30,000 workers of Clait Hospital caused
disruptions in clinics and administrative offices. And the
country's 1,250 firefighters handled only emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The union leaders met today to discuss spreading the
disruptions to other sectors of the economy throughout the public
sector. Negotiations between government workers and the Finance
Ministry on salaries, working conditions, pensions, and government
privatization plans have broken down.
</P>
<P>
The trade union is objecting to various elements of government
policy, including the proposed 2.3 billion shekel (about 657
million U.S. dollars) state budget cut for 1998, plans to
privatize many government companies and what it sees as ongoing
attacks on worker's rights throughout the public sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
