<HEADLINE> PNA Minister Unsure About Outcome of Albright's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 14 (Xinhua) - A senior Palestinian official
said here today that it was still early to say whether
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's trip to the region
was successful or not.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of her visit depended on what conclusion Albright
would submit to U.S. President Clinton, visiting Minister of
Local Government of Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Saeb
Erekat told reporters after briefing Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali and Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh on the
recent talks between Palestinian leadership and Albright.
</P>
<P>
It was premature to jump into conclusion about the outcome of
Albright's maiden trip to the region, Erekat said before the
U.S. secretary of state's scheduled visit to Amman this evening.
</P>
<P>
Amman is the last leg of her current trip which has already
taken her to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria, Egypt
and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister added, it would take more than one
visit by Albright to repair the damages inflicted on the peace
process by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinians and the U.S. could work together to
lay the foundation or mechanism to ensure the full implementation
of all the signed agreements between the Palestinians and Israel,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians cherished the U.S.'s efforts to help resume
the peace process, especially as the Middle East as a whole now
stood at a juncture, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He made the comments amid signs that the parties concerned
believed that Albright has failed to achieve her expectations to
revive the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
Erekat arrived here this morning to convey a message to King
Hussein of Jordan from Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat as part
of the ongoing coordination between the Palestinians and the
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state launched her trip to the Middle
East Wednesday in coincidence with the 4th anniversary of the
signing of the Oslo peace accords on September 13, 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to agreements between Israel and the Palestinians,
Israel should evacuate most areas of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
at the beginning of this month, but Israel has not lived up to its
promises yet.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations have been stalled
since Israel started to build a controversial Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
