<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provinces Join in Cultural Promotion Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Three Chinese provinces in
the Yellow River Valley, the birthplace of the nation's culture
some 5,000 years ago, have joined in carrying out a series of
cultural promotion projects in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi and Shanxi Province in northwest China, and Henan
Province in central China are home to thousands of historical
relics and each has a long history of culture and art.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to enhance the development of cultural
resources and further promote tourism, the three provincial
governments have introduce training programs for local cultural
officials and tour guides who will help tourists from across the
world gain greater insight into Chinese history and tradition.
</P>
<P>
The provincial governments have sponsored a number of
historical relics exhibitions with a variety of themes, including
"Women of the Tang Dynasty (618-907)"; "Collection of Ancient Jade
Ware"; "Bronze Article Display"; and "Reproductions Fair", which
featured 500 varieties of historical relic replica.
</P>
<P>
The provincial tourism bureaus have jointly developed 10
special tourism programs which focus on cultural sites and
historical relics. Five tour itineraries have been selected during
an international trade fair for central and west China.
</P>
<P>
In addition, archeologists in the provinces have conducted
extensive historical research projects and published numerous
academic papers on cultural relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Paintings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
invited over 100 artists to draw paintings highlighting the Three
Gorges on the Yangtze River, a famous tourist area and future home
of the world's largest dam.
</P>
<P>
The painters have created colorful works to forever preserve the
splendor and beauty of the Three Gorges as it is today.
</P>
<P>
The work has been carried out over the past two years and an
exhibition is being held in Changsha, capital of Hunan province,
to pay tribute to the massive construction project which will dam
the Yangtze later this year.
</P>
<P>
Renowned masters, including the 89-year-old He Haixia, have
participated in the project which will preserve the cultural color
for the Three Gorges Project.  
</P>
