<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continuing Violence Hits Kenya's Coast Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The continuing violence in
the coast region of Kenya during the past one month has dealt a
serious blow to the country's tourism sector with massive
cancellations and no new hotel bookings recorded.
</P>
<P>
Today's Sunday Nation said that hotel bookings in the coast
region had dropped by over 50 percent following the recent
violent actions in the tourists' resort of Mombasa and its
environs.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Chairman of the Mombasa and Coast Tourist
Association Najib Balala as saying on Friday that there were no
new bookings for the coming season.
</P>
<P>
A hotelier at the north coast of Mombasa said that since the
violence starting with an attack on police stations at Likoni
area on August 13, the tourism sector had suffered a loss of
about 10 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure is set to increase owing to the continuing
insecurity in the region which had led to a death toll of over 60
in the past one month, he added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Somak Tours Ltd. said that a travel firm with
which they had signed a contract to bring in 300 tourists per
week from Hungary had canceled their bookings.
</P>
<P>
Joash Olum, Managing Director of Somak Tours, noted that "This
is the saddest moment in the tourism sector since independence
and we fear unless the violence is curbed, the tourism sector
will collapse."
</P>
<P>
If more tourists cancel their bookings, while at same time no
new bookings are recorded, all the key players in the tourism
industry would be forced to close down, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Tourism and Wildlife Protas Momanyi is on
a tourism campaign trip to the United Kingdom to reassure British
tourists that Kenya is a safe destination for holiday makers.
</P>
<P>
The minister's promotion campaign in Britain is aimed at
preventing further decline in tourist arrivals following the
recent violence in coast region.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry is the number one foreign exchange earner for
the east African country which received 770,000 tourists with an
earning of 480 million Dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
