<HEADLINE> China to Host Musical Instrument Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Changsha, capital of central
China's Hunan Province, will host a December exhibition of
traditional Chinese musical instruments dating back some 3,000
years to Shang and Yin Dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The 76 instruments on display will include inverted bronze
bells, small cymbals, and a series of ceremonial musical
paraphernalia, according to Tan Weisi, an archeologist with the
provincial museum.
</P>
<P>
"Archeologists in the province have unearthed numerous ancient
musical instruments in recent years," said Tan. He pointed out
that nine bronze cymbals unearthed in 1993 dated the nation's
history of musical performance to some 3,000 years ago, or 1,000
years earlier than previous records.
</P>
<P>
Experts have engaged in extensive scientific research on relics
discovered in Hunan, said Tan, adding that related studies have
verified that musical instruments played an important role in
ancient Chinese culture and art history.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will feature performances of ancient music by 10
Chinese artists using replicas of ancient musical instruments.
</P>
</TEXT>
