<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lesotho Still Faces Political Crisis (by Liu Yegang) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Political crisis in
Lesotho, which culminated recently by several political events,
is creating an unstable climate which could damage the kingdom's
struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has pervaded Lesotho since Prime Minister Ntsu
Mokhehle decided on July 9 to leave the ruling Basotholand
Congress Party (BCP). He took 40 MPs with him, leaving 24 MPs
with the BCP.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's move to transfer powers of the ruling party to his
new party, the Lesotho Congress for Democracy, followed a BCP
congress in which Mokhehle was voted out as party leader.
</P>
<P>
Since then mass demonstrations have been organized by the BCP
and other organizations which argue that Mokhehle's move was
unconstitutional as he stripped the ruling party of its
powers before an election had been held.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle, in turn, argued that his move is legal because he
has the support of the majority of MPs.
</P>
<P>
The situation took a turn for the worse in August when
parliament Speaker, John Kolane, announced that three BCP MPs,
including BCP's chairman, had been suspended from parliament.
</P>
<P>
They were suspended after telling the speaker he had no
business to declare the BCP the official opposition as the party
had won the previous elections.
</P>
<P>
A few days later, the speaker announced that the media and
members of the public could no longer attend parliament debate,
and the police were ordered to escort them out.
</P>
<P>
The ban has not yet been lifted, even though journalists
petitioned the speaker, saying the order violated constitutional
guarantees on freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the speaker asked the police to eject the
remaining BCP MPs from parliament after they refused to follow
parliamentary procedures as an expression of defiance at his
declaration that the BCP had become the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders in Lesotho said the protracted political
impasse would damage the country's chances of recovery after its
implementing economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the present crisis continued, the economy
would deteriorate to the point that Lesotho would not be able to
service its foreign debt, and unemployment would rocket.
</P>
<P>
The decision to bar BCP MPs from parliament has generated
widespread anger, promoting the senate, which is pro-BCP, and BCP
MPs to write to King Letsie, asking him to intervene in upholding
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The BCP has been supported in opposing Mokhehle's moves by the
senate, traditional chiefs, the organized youth and women's
groups as well as the church.
</P>
<P>
They have all taken part in marches on the Royal Palace to
petition the king to dissolve Mokhehle's government.
</P>
<P>
Since then the king has appointed members of the Electoral
Commission who were sworn in last week.
</P>
<P>
Southern African leaders have called on the king to make more
efforts to stablize the situation through political reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 14) - 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- (At Xinhua's request, some
delegates to the current 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) write what they see, discuss and think during
the congress in diary form, which we think will provide outsiders
with some information about this major event. The following diary,
the fourth of its kind, was written by Professor Ren Yanshen, Party
Secretary of Beijing University. -- Ed.)
</P>
<P>
Along with some of my fellow delegates from the educational
circle, I was invited to give my opinions about the draft report
to the current Congress.
</P>
<P>
We put forward some suggestions on the strategy of developing
the country through science, technology and education, as well as
the policy toward the intellectuals in the new period.
</P>
<P>
I'm glad to hear that the report delivered by Jiang Zemin at
the opening session of the congress has fully incorporated our
opinions, in that the parts concerning science, technology and
education and the intellectuals have been substantiated.
</P>
<P>
A small example as it is, it proves that the report has
pooled the wisdom of the delegates.
</P>
<P>
The issues of science, technology and education have been
fully expounded in the report.
</P>
<P>
Some of its remarks, including "progress of science and
technology is a decisive factor behind the economic development",
"Competent people are the most important resources for scientific
and technological progress and economic and social development",
"We must see to it that education is given a strategic priority",
and that "the whole party must fully understand that cultural
advancement is essential and urgent because it plays a great role
in developing the cause of socialism and rejuvenating the nation",
are essential remarks that I hope could be fully recognized
throughout the Party and the entire society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 14) - 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Universities are confronted with quite a few substantial
problems, yet they enjoy great advantages and potentials, which
lie in their advanced culture, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
We should tap the potentials in these aspects and make them
applicable for the society.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Beijing University boasts a strong teaching
faculty with professors alone numbering over 800. Every year, a
total of 3,000 to 4,000 students graduated from the school.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University ranks the first among the universities
across the country, whether in terms of the number of key
subjects, or the number of key laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The departments of natural science and technology in the
school, for instance, carry out 600 to 700 research projects
annually.
</P>
<P>
Once this vast resource is applied, the modernization drive in
the country will benefit a lot. And in turn, a new situation will
be created in the school.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University is about to celebrate its 100th founding
anniversary around the turn of the century. Once the country's
pioneer to dissemilate Marxism and scientific and democratic
ideas, the university made key contributions to the victory of the
Chinese revolution and the country's socialist construction.
</P>
<P>
In the forthcoming 21st century, Beijing University will
undoubtedly carry forward the tradition, and contribute more to
the cause of building socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 14) - 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In my opinion, the strategy of developing the country through
science, technology and education can be regarded as a basic
national policy closely related to the overall modernization drive
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the strategy, I think, is not arbitrary
nor dispensable, but a feasible approach fitting the reality of
the country.
</P>
<P>
It is a fundamental strategy to be introduced considering the
the fact that competitions in economic and scientific strength
in the world are becoming acute.
</P>
<P>
For colleges and universities, the introduction of the
strategy is a historical opportunity to be treasured.
</P>
<P>
At present, we should pay attention to two issues in education,
the "orientation" and the "adaptation".
</P>
<P>
The "orientation" means the purpose of education. In the final
analysis, I think that education should serve the modernization
drive in the country.
</P>
<P>
As for "adaptation", I think that everything done, including the
educational setup, content of courses and the cultivation of
competent personnel, should serve the needs in economic
construction and social development.
</P>
<P>
Education should serve the requirements of economic
construction and the modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Never before have I found that the economic and social
development strongly needs education. Nor have I so clearly seen
the general trend that the values of knowledge and talented people
have risen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
