<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Blames US for EU ban of Pistachios </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's agriculture minister
today accused the United States of being behind the imposition
of the temporary ban by the Council of the European Union on the
importation of Iranian pistachio.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, the minister, Issa
Kalantari, once again defended the quality of the Iranian pistachio
banned temporarily in Europe for possible health hazards while
attacking the United States for trying to take over the European
market.
</P>
<P>
He that "Iranian pistachio is not contaminated, but it is the
healthiest type of pistachio. The level of contamination of the
pistachio exported out of Iran is below the standards that the
client recommended to us."
</P>
<P>
Pistachio has turned into another dispute between Iran and
the EU, which recalled its ambassadors from Tehran last April in
the aftermath of the Berlin Court ruling that implicated Iranian
leaders in the killing of four Kurdish opposition leaders in the
Mykonos restaurant five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The EU Council said that it had banned imports of pistachios
from Iran because of fears of contamination by Aflatoxin B1, a
carcinogenic substance produced by molds.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that the Americans are behind this (ban). They can
not fully take our place in Europe, but they can lie and make
European people worry that Iranian pistachio is contaminated,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "then the Americans themselves would be able to
sell their pistachio at any rate they please. Already the
pistachio prices have gone up by 20 percent."
</P>
<P>
Kalantari added that Iran had the lion's share of European
market for pistachio because it fulfilled 96 percent of the
European demand for pistachio. Iran exported 90,000 tonnes of
pistachio to Europe last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the contaminated container, which triggered the
EU's decision to impose ban on Iranian pistachio until December
15, had been re-exported by an UAE merchant to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister urged the Europeans to approach the
issue from a more rational, expert-like angle, rather than try
to politicize the matter, saying "independent world bodies such
as World Health Organization or Food and Agriculture Organization
can come to Iran where we grow and package pistachio and test
our pistachio."
</P>
<P>
Pistachio fetches Iran about 400 million U.S. dollars
annually and provides 350,000 jobs. Some 400,000 hectares of
land are allocated for growing pistachio in Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
