<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Oslo Accords Must Be Followed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright has affirmed that the agreements reached
in Oslo could not be given up as they are the foundations of the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Her remarks came in the Egyptian TV program "Good Morning,
Egypt" broadcast today.
</P>
<P>
"Public opinion in the region wants peace, and leaders of the
nations concerned ought to make big decisions to fulfill this
wish," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreements signed four years ago in Washington started
the Middle East peace process which has been deadlocked due to
Israeli government's policies on issues like Jewish settlement
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the proposal by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to intensify the final-status talks with Palestinians
instead of making further redeployment of Israeli troops in the
West Bank, Albright denied she is for the proposal.
</P>
<P>
She said speeding up the final-status talks and implementing
the existing agreements have to go parallel.
</P>
<P>
On her current trip to the region, Albright said she has managed
to make but minor steps in restoring confidence between the
Palestinians and Israelis, adding major steps are needed "because
both the Israeli and Palestinians peoples want peace."
</P>
<P>
Albright started her trip to Israel on September 10, her first
to the region since taking office early this year. She has also
visited Palestinian-ruled areas, Syria, Egypt and Saudi
Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
