<HEADLINE> World Bank Resumes Funding of Nigeria's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has resumed its
funding of Nigeria's 7.5 million U.S. Dollar national population
program, the Guardian newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The program was initiated in 1991 to study the impact of the
Nigerian population, the biggest population in Africa, on the
country's national development.
</P>
<P>
It was then funded by the World Bank under the auspices of the
United Nation's Development and Poverty Alienation Program in the
third world countries.
</P>
<P>
The bank stopped funding the program in 1995 in the crisis
sparked off by Nigeria's annulment of the June 12, 1993
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The decision to restart the program was made in a recent
meeting in Abuja, the Nigerian capital, which were attended by
the World Bank, the Nigerian Ministry of Health and other
agencies involved.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that the program will be finished by the
end of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
