<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Fund Managers Confident of Malaysian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign fund managers
are happy with the Malaysian government's policies taken recently
to tackle its economic woes and are confident of the long-term
prospects of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 fund managers from the United States, the United
Kingdom and Singapore had a 90-minute dialogue here today with
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad who returned home
earlier this morning from a week-long visit to Mongolia and
Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
Expressing their sympathy with Malaysia's recent predicament,
particularly the volatility in the stock and currency markets, the
managers felt that the Malaysian government has put in place the
right policies to tackle some of its economic woes, especially
that of the persistent current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after the dialogue, James Alexandroff from
the fund management firm of Arisaig Partners from Singapore said,
"Nothing Mahathir said gave us any cause for concern...on the
contrary, we were reassured in many ways and we are more confident
about the economy now that the right policies are being
undertaken."
</P>
<P>
David Roche, from London-based Independent Strategy, said that
to build up foreign direct investor confidence, Malaysia needs to
do three major things including a definite move to run a bigger
fiscal surplus, using the currency decline as an opportunity to
increase exports and improve returns on capital, and making sure
that monetary policy is supportive of the currency and that things
are getting better.
</P>
<P>
"If these three elements fall into place, we can have a very
quick bounce back not only in the ringgit but also in the
financial markets, as well as in confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is able to achieve, as Deputy Prime Minister and
Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim said last week, a growth rate in
excess of eight percent this year and in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
