<HEADLINE> World Economic Development Congress to Be Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth Annual World
Economic Development Congress, which is of significant relevance
to infrastructure development in rapidly expanding Asian
economies, is expected to be held in Hong Kong between September
16 and 18.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 delegates from around the world, including some 100
government ministers, are expected to attend the conference, with
keynote speakers including Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa, former US Secretary
of State George Shultz, and Nobel laureate and economist Milton
Friedman.
</P>
<P>
The congress features a host of concurrent summits covering the
major infrastructure sectors such as global telecommunications,
private power, transportation, water supply and waste water
treatment, and logistics and distribution.
</P>
<P>
As an independent and non-affiliated conference, the congress
was established in 1992 as a forum for the public and private
sectors to interact and discuss economic issues facing the world,
Vidar Jorgensen, founder and chairman of the congress, told a
press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Every year the congress is convened at a time immediately prior
to the World Bank/International Monetary Fund (WB/IMF) Annual
Meetings, and at the same place as that of the WB/IMF meetings, to
attract a higher attendance of business executives and government
leaders, according to President of the congress Barbara
Grufferman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
