<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Tourism Makes Huge Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has made
huge profit from tourism in the past nine years, Acting Executive
Director of the Tourism Business Council Colin Walker said at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Tourism had earned 26.8 billion Rand (5.7 billion U.S.Dollars)
in 1996 with domestic tourists spending 14.8 billion (3.1 billion
U.S. Dollars) and foreign tourists 12 billion Rand (2.6 billion
U.S. Dollars), Walker told a seminar in Durban on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Targets set for growth in tourism until 2000 were to increase
froeign exchange earnings from 13 billion Rand (2.8 billion U.S.
Dollars) a year to 23 billion Rand (4.9 billion U.S.Dollars).
</P>
<P>
This meant South African travels services should host 2.2
million overseas visitors and increase the number of domestic
holiday trips to 19,500 a year, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
The tourism target is also aimed to raise employment from
550,000 to 860,000 jobs and double the number of tourism ventures
owned or operated by disadvantaged entrepreneurs and communities,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
