<HEADLINE> Damage to S.African Black Activist's Statue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging's Acronym Awb was spray-painted in
bold, black letters on the plinth of the 2.2 m-high Biko's statue, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa on Friday commemorated the death of Biko, who died 20
years ago while held in police custody as a political detainee.
</P>
<P>
Political leaders across the spectrum have voiced their disgust at
the desecration of the Biko's Statue, noting that the criminal act was
designed to erase Biko's memory in the minds of the black majority.
</P>
<P>
"They (extrimists) can deface Biko's statue but they cannot remove
his memory," Azanian People's Organization President Mosibudi Mangena
said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress spokesperson Ronnie Mamoepa
called the defacing of the statue an affront to the majority of people
in South Africa and said his party condemned the act "as a racist
deed".
</P>
<P>
"We call on law enforcement agencies to do their utmost to track
down the perpetrators of this dastardly deed and to ensure they face
the full might of the law," Mamoepa said.
</P>
<P>
Pan Africanist Congress Secretary-General Mike Muendane said the
"Animal or amimals" who had defaced the state wanted to cause chaos in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It is an obvious act of madness, solely aimed at derailing
progress," he added.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party Leader Tony Leon called on the might of the laws
to hunt down the perpetrators and prosecute them as their act is "an
affront to the reconciliation process" in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
