<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Strives to Cut Poor and Hungry Households </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 14 (xinhua) -- Vietnam has been cutting the
number of poor and hungry households by two percent annually in
recent years, official Vietnam News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is striving to reduce the number of hungry households
by 180,000 and the poor by 250,000.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Vietnam has nearly 2.9 million poor households
accounting for 19.3 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Households in mountainous and rural regions with monthly per
capita income equivalent to 15 kg of rice (40,000 dong or 3.4
dollars) are considered "poor," while in urban areas, the level is
20 kg to 25 kg of rice (50,000 dong to 65,000 dong or 4.3 dollars to 5.5
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The national program of hunger eradication and poverty
alleviation will receive an estimated 2,157 billion dong (about
184 million dollars) from the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The total state-budget allocations for the program reached
3,000 billion dong (roughly 256 million dollars) in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
