<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz has urged the United States to put pressure on Israel
to end its aggression against the Palestinian people and to honor
the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd made the call in his talks with visiting
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Saturday night, during
which both sides discussed means of pushing forward the Middle
East peace process and achieving just and comprehensive peace in
the region, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Fahd expressed concern over Israel's aggressiveness, as well as
its collective punishment against the Palestinians, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, both sides also dealt with the bilateral
relations and the security of the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived in the Saudi Red Sea city of Jeddah earlier
Saturday after visiting Israel, Palestinian self-ruled areas,
Syria and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
This is her maiden Mideast trip since taking office in January,
which is aimed at reviving the stalled Mideast peace-making. But
observers here put her trip a failure, as it just resulted in a
decision to have the advisors of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat hold talks in
Washington in two weeks time.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due to leave for Saudi southern resort of Abha this
morning to meet the foreign ministers of the six Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states for talks over the relations between the
U.S. and GCC states, the Mideast peace process, Gulf security,
Iran's new policy and their stance toward the economic conference
for the Mideast and North Africa scheduled to be held in the Qatari
capital of Doha in November.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
