<HEADLINE> China to Cut Tariffs by 26 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to bring
its import and export tariff rates down from 23 percent to 17
percent on average as of October 1 this year, the Office of the
Customs Tariff Commission of the State Council has announced.
</P>
<P>
The cut, scaling down by 26 percent, will affect more than
4,800 items accounting for over 73 percent of the total
tariff-imposed commodities, officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said that this is another big cut made by China on its own
to meet the development of its national economy, and it is an
important measure adopted by China to deepen the reforms and
increase opening up.
</P>
<P>
"The move fully demonstrates China's determination and
confidence in taking part in international competition and
cooperation in a more open attitude," they said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993 China has cut tariffs on its own several times. The
tariff rates have been brought down by 60 percent over the past
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Issue Not To Cause Social Unrest: Labor Minister (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official said here
today that although deepening economic reform will cause certain
pressure on employment, it will by no means touch off social
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Li Boyong, a delegate to the on-going 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China, said deepening reforms in
state-owned enterprises will bring about certain pressure on
employment in urban areas in China, but it is within the handling
capacity of the society, and is far from touching off any social
unrest.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also minister of labor, quoted the report delivered
by Jiang Zemin at the congress as saying, "With the deepening of
enterprise reforms, technological progress and readjustment of the
economic structure, it would be hard to avoid the flow of
personnel and lay-off."
</P>
<P>
"But no such 'disastrous outcome' as predicted by some overseas
figures will go off," Li emphasized.
</P>
<P>
As far as Li was concerned, the employment situation in China
faces both challenges and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Li explained that while the number of laid-off workers is to
increase in the wake of further reforms in state businesses, rapid
development in non-public sectors and joint stock partnership
businesses, on the other hand, will undoubtedly offer more job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The abundant labor resource in China, which totals 834 million
in number, does pose quite a headache to the country's employment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Each year, there are 10 million more people seeking jobs in
towns and cities. Many of them come from surplus factory worker
forces, which stand at a staggering 20 million.
</P>
<P>
In addition, approximately 130 million peasants have become idle
in the rural areas, and may compete with urbanites for jobs.
</P>
<P>
However, Li said, the ongoing reemployment project has scored
great achievements. Each year from 1992 to 1996, the newly
employed outnumbered the laid-offs by a margin of eight million,
thus maintaining an annual unemployment rate in urban areas at
about 3 percent throughout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Issue Not To Cause Social Unrest: Labor Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Ministry of Labor has adopted a series of measures against
unemployment," said Li.
</P>
<P>
A job preparatory system has been established in cities and
towns demanding that each person receive pre-job trainings that
may last one to three years.
</P>
<P>
As for idle farmers, job opportunities in the vicinity of their
habitats have been offered, while management of the trans-regional
flow of peasant laborers has been strengthened, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
The main problem still lies with surplus workers in urban
areas, Li said. It is estimated that a total of 8.14 million
workers were laid off last year.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, assistance with laid-off workers in seeking jobs
has become the key item in the reemployment project.
</P>
<P>
"Over five million laid-off workers have been involved in the
project across the country," said Li. "And half of them have
already found new jobs."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has adopted measures to protect those
workers with unemployment insurance and the lowest living standard
security system, one to prevail in all cities by the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential that laid-off workers change their traditional
ideas and be brave enough to seek jobs out of state enterprises,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In Li's opinion, the country has a lot potential to tap in its
job market. The number of employees engaged in service trade, for
instance, only takes up 26 percent of the total employed in 1996,
while that of developed countries has already topped 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister was confident that the unemployment rate in urban
areas could be controlled within 4 percent by the end of this
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
