<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Singapore Continues Suffering From Heavy Haze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is suffering from
continued heavy haze which has blurred the air quality to an
unhealthy level, as Indonesia is stepping up its efforts to fight
land and forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring Malaysia, also seriously affected, has turned to
Western countries for help.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, haze worsened to beyond the 100 reading on the
24-hour Pollutant Standards Index (PSI), which is considered
unhealthy. The index reached 106, the worst level so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
The haze, which began appearing four weeks ago, is caused by
winds blowing smoke from large-scale land and forest fires in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that doctors here were seeing at least
20 percent more patient with respiratory problems since the haze
started. One doctor was quoted as saying that people were
experiencing runny eyes, more nasal discharge and throat problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that breathing such air with haze can be as bad as
cigarette smoke but the effects are more transient.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said that a few number of flights from
Singapore to Indonesia were canceled on Saturday because of the
heavy hazy weather.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, seriously affected by the worsening haze, has turned
to France and Canada for help to combat the haze hanging over the
country.
</P>
<P>
Science, Technology and Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng
Ding said officials from the embassies of the two Western
countries were helping the Malaysian government to map out an
action plan to tackle the haze problem nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Datuk Law, who is to travel to Jakarta this week to discuss the
problem, said that France and Canada, due to their well-known
experiences in putting out forest fires, can offer Malaysia the
appropriate solution.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has declared the haze situation, the worst in three
years, as a national disaster, because the air quality has
deteriorated to "very unhealthy" levels in various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, anticipating that the haze problem will worsen in
the weeks ahead, spelt out on Saturday measures it was taking to
prevent more fires in the forest and plantation areas of Sumatra
and Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
The measures, ranging from cloud-seeding operation in "hot
spot" areas to the setting up of a national coordinating agency
for land fires, underscored the seriousness with which the
government was tackling the problem.
</P>
<P>
The measures are being taken against the backdrop of worsening
climatic conditions in Indonesia, which is experiencing its worst
drought for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Forest fires in Kalimantan and Sumatra, and the resulting smoke
and haze affecting the region, were the result of land clearing
activities by forestry and plantation firms and, as a senior
Indonesian government official said, had destroyed more than
300,000 hectares of forest as of July this year.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Service of Singapore has ruled out
cloud-seeding operation as a way to deal with the haze here. A
statement from the department said Singapore was too small, and
clouds created may be blown away before they can bring rain.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the rain produced by such clouds will provide only
temporary relief as the haze will continue to be blown in by the
prevailing winds, it added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
