<HEADLINE> Farmer/Musician's Dreams Come True </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A 78-year-old
farmer/songwriter in north China recently saw his dreams come true
when one of his song collections was published and a music school
named after him set up.
</P>
<P>
Shi Zhangyuan was born in a small village in north China's
Shanxi Province. Throughout his youth, he wrote songs when he
wasn't working in the fields. So far, he's composed more than
2,000 tunes.
</P>
<P>
"The founding of new China in 1949 brought a happy life to our
poor farmers, which inspired me to write songs," said the old man,
who was in his twenties at the time and already an accomplished
musician.
</P>
<P>
In the 50 years since, Shi has devoted his spare time to
writing songs, one after another. His tunes first became favorites
among his fellow villagers, then in the province, and some became
hits nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"Late Premier Zhou Enlai personally conducted one of my songs
titled 'Welcome to Our Village'," Shi said with pride. Another
composition won the top prize in a national competition.
</P>
<P>
"I had two dreams in my life: one to have my song books
published, and another to set up a school in our village to
popularize music education among children," Shi said. But he
lacked the money to do it on his own.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Shanghai Opera and Dance Theater heard about
Shi, and decided to donate their total ticket sales from a
performance of "Romeo and Juliet" to set up a primary school named
after the prolific musician.
</P>
<P>
A year later, a book with 70 of Shi's songs was published in
Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
