<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotel Occupancy Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The average occupancy rate of
Chinese hotels has been falling over the past one and a half
years, according to a survey by the Ministry of Internal Trade.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the 1996 occupancy rate for Beijing's
hotels were 50 percent; Harbin's, 37.4 percent; and Jinan's, 58
percent. In the first half of this year, the average hotel
occupancy rate dropped eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Luxury hotels have generally fared better than the inexpensive
accommodations, and non-State-owned hotels did better than
state-owned ones.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts explain that the falling rate was the result
of too many new hotels built, which makes the total number of
hotel rooms exceed the market demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
