<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wuhan Builds Databank on Local Talents Living Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A databank on local people who
have gone abroad for study is being created in this capital city
of central China's Hubei province.
</P>
<P>
The move is to accommodate the needs of local businesses and
institutions seeking to draw in more talents and overseas students
who want to find jobs in their hometown.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1980s, Wuhan has sent more than
10,000 people abroad for study. However, no follow-up record has
been kept on the whereabouts of these overseas students, who can
play an important role in promoting local development.
</P>
<P>
The city science commission started last May to establish a
databank of overseas talent to set up contact with them. The city
also hopes, through them, to introduce more funding and
technology, and launch Sino-foreign cooperative research and
development projects.
</P>
<P>
The commission has issued a registration form, to be completed
by overseas scientific and technological personnel from Wuhan, to
43 higher education institutions and more than 20 research
institutes in the city, and so far 140 of the forms have been
returned.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the commission said they will complete the
initial work on the databank at the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
