<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark Wins Both Singles Badminton Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Poul Erik Hoyer Larsen of
Denmark defeated compatriot Peter Gade-Christensen 15-6, 7-15 and
15-6 to take the men's singles title at the U.S. Open Badminton
Championships in California on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The Danish Olympic champion, who ranked fourth in the world,
thus received 13,000 U.S. dollars for his hard victory.
</P>
<P>
The women's singles title was taken by Denmark's top-seeded
Camilla Martin who rallied to beat second-seeded Dai Yun of China
11-4, 6-11, 12-10.
</P>
<P>
Martin who ranked fifth in the world, overcame a 10-7 deficit
in the final game.
</P>
<P>
South Korea Kim Dong Moon, Olympic champion in the mixed
doubles, become the twice champion by taking the men's and mixed
doubles.
</P>
<P>
Kim teamed with Ra Kyung Min to beat Indonesian Bambang
Suprianto and Rosalina Riseu 15-1, 15-3 in the mixed doubles
before winning the men's doubles with partner Ha Tae Kwan.
</P>
<P>
Kim and Ha outwitted Chinese Zhang Wei and Liu Yong 15-3, 6-15
and 15-12 by rallying from a 7-10 deficit in the decider game.
</P>
<P>
The mixed doubles was Kim's third consecutive win at the
U.S. Open, all with different partners. Only England's Mike
Butler had achieved such a feat in the Open history.
</P>
<P>
In the women's doubles, China's top-seeded Tang Yongshu and Qin
Yiyuan routed second-seeded Yoshiko Iwata and Haruko Matsuda of
Japan 15-6, 15-2. 
