<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merger to Foster Petrochemical Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The proposed merger of four
petrochemical companies in east China's Jiangsu Province is
expected to create an internationally competitive conglomerate,
according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The State Council has chosen Li Yizhong, executive
vice-president of China Petrochemical Corporation (Sinopec), as
director of the preparatory committee for the merger.
</P>
<P>
The four companies are: Yizheng Chemical Fiber Group Corp,
Yangzi Petrochemical Corp, Jinling Petrochemical Co. and Nanjing
Chemical Industrial Group. They are located within 30 kilometers
of one another on the banks of the Yangtze River near Nanjing,
capital city of Jiangsu.
</P>
<P>
Although the four companies have similar production structures,
they fall under the jurisdiction of different administrative
departments, including Sinopec, the China National Textile Council
and the Jiangsu Provincial Government, which makes co-ordination
and co-operation difficult.
</P>
<P>
the State Council decided to launch the merger after careful
research, Li said.
</P>
<P>
It is a key step in China's strategy of organizing large
industrial groups to revamp State-owned enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new petrochemical group will be able to sharpen its
competitiveness in the domestic and international market", he
said, it is vital for China's State enterprises to combine their
efforts to compete with foreign giants.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerate would become China's largest petrochemical
producer. The aggregate capital of the four companies was 45
billion yuan (5.42 billion US dollars) last year, and their
turnover was 33 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The group will be able to refine and process 10 million tons of
crude oil annually. It will have an annual capacity of one million
tons of chemical fertilizer, 900,000 tons of phthalic acid,
850,000 tons of arene, 800,000 tons of polyester and 400,000 tons
of ethylene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
