<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steps to Avert Congestion at Chittagong Port Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
considering taking immediate steps to avert further congestion at
the Chittagong Port, the much-troubled economic lifeline of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The steps would be giving Inland Container Depot (ICD) in the
private sector the authority to deal with both export and import
business, according to port sources.
</P>
<P>
The port congestion at Chittagong has hit the country's foreign
trade as the feeder vessel operators frequently impose congestion
surcharges on the containers used for import and export business.
</P>
<P>
On September 1, the vessel owners imposed a punitive congestion
surcharge as a result of shortage of space in container yards and
a strike by trade unions in July. The surcharge, however, was
removed five days later following a plea by the port authorities.
</P>
<P>
"If the private sector ICDs are allowed to handle the
containers both for import and export business, the congestion
situation in the Chittagong Port will be improved a lot," said a
port user.
</P>
<P>
The National Board of Revenue (NBR) opposed the idea of giving
private ICDs the power to deal with foreign trade business for
fear of loss of government revenue.
</P>
<P>
But the NBR authority has now accepted the proposal. "We are
now working on the modalities on how the private ICDs can handle
container cargo both for export and import," said a senior officer
of the NBR.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the port authority believed that man-made acts,
especially labor troubles, were one of the major causes for the
port congestion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
