<HEADLINE> Battle to Put out Mt Kilimanjaro Fire Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A battle is going on by
about 260 Tanzanian game rangers, civilians and policemen to
contain a fire which erupted at Mt Kilimanjaro, northern
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The fire that started last Friday has sealed off two ascending
routes on the western flank of the mountain, according to reports
available here today.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director General of the Tanzania National Parks, Gerald
Bigumbi said on Saturday that they have succeeded to halt the
fire from spreading to the west-northern side. Efforts are on to
completely put out the blaze.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, despite the temporary closure of the two
routes, tourists are free to use the four other routes for
ascending, which are safe.
</P>
<P>
The chief park warden of the Kilimanjaro National Park, Lorivi
Ole-Moirana also said on Saturday that they have managed to
control the fire in the area where it erupted by creating
firebreakers.
</P>
<P>
The fire is not much devastative compared to another one in
January which lasted for two and half months and destroyed 3,000
hectares, he said, adding, "I'm hopeful we'll put out this fire
soon."
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire is not known and still under
investigation. 
</P>
