<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key State Firms Set to Revive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The painstaking effort to
prune State-owned enterprises will pay off in about 10 years,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Such firms accounted for 80 percent of China's industrial
output in the 1970s, said a senior official of the State
Statistics Bureau (SSB), adding that the the proportion has
plunged to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In fact, less than 30 percent would be sufficient if the State
has effective control in six or seven key sectors vital to
economic growth, said Li Qiming, director of the bureau's industry
and transportation department.
</P>
<P>
His remarks reflect a growing consensus among Chinese leaders
and economists that socialism does not have to rely solely upon
State ownership.
</P>
<P>
A prevailing State ownership in the 1960s and 1970s spoiled the
Chinese economy, leaving no room for private business.
</P>
<P>
Li ruled out privatization as a panacea for China battling to
bail out its teetering State enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said the bulk of such firms would become collectively owned
through shareholding, including internal holding of shares by
employees.
</P>
<P>
State and collective firms make up about 80 percent of the
country's industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Li said the private sector would grow, but privatization was
out of the question.
</P>
<P>
"The policy has paid off to support a selected number of large
State enterprises while leaving most smaller ones sink or swim on
their own," Li said.
</P>
<P>
State industrial enterprises posted positive profits in the
first half of this year, an initial recovery from a net deficit in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
About 36,000 State industrial firms have annual sales income of
more than five million yuan (600,000 US dollars). Although they
account for 41 percent of those firms, their sales income and
industrial output makes up more than 95 percent of the nation's
total respectively, Li said.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, the 36,000 enterprises contributed to 113
percent of total profits of State industrial firms, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls on Gulf States to Remove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has called on Gulf countries to remove all
misunderstanding between them in a bid to enhance Islamic
solidarity, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed that attempts to preserve security and
stability of the Persian Gulf is the common objective of Iran
and other friendly countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Two English dailies Tehran Times and Iran News reported that
Khatami made the remarks while meeting with visiting Qatari
Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Bin Jaber al Thani here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari foreign minister delivered a message from Qatar
Emir Sheikh Hamad Ben Khalifa Al Thani who confirmed that a high-
ranking Qatari delegation would attend the summit of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) scheduled here in
December.
</P>
<P>
Khatami was quoted as saying that the regional countries
should deal with each other with respect and understanding in
order to remove all misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran supports any activity to promote unity
and understanding among the Persian Gulf countries and preserve
the region's security.
</P>
<P>
"Iran's relations with other countries is only based on
mutual respect," he said, adding that "bilateral relations based
on this principle can be model for other countries."
</P>
<P>
Good-neighborliness is one of the main principles of Iran's
foreign policy, especially in its ties with the regional
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said undoubtedly there are other common grounds for
cooperation between Iran and other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed further activation of Iran-Qatar Joint
Commission and said it would pave the way for speedy
implementation of bilateral contracts.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president urged the regional countries to try to
construct an atmosphere of mutual confidence and to remove
misunderstandings in a bid to foil the ploys of some countries
which want the region to remain underdeveloped and exposed to
threats.
</P>
<P>
"Under such pretexts they can increase their illegitimate
military presence in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari foreign minister, who arrived here Friday night,
said that Qatar's ties with its neighbors, Iran in particular,
are solid.
</P>
<P>
He said that in his meetings with Iranian officials he
intended to become familiar with Tehran's views and discuss
further expansion of Tehran-Doha ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
