<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Hold Peace Talks With Tribal rebels today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
resume peace talks here today with tribal rebels in a fresh bid to
end the decades-old insurgency in southern Chittagong Hill Tracts
(CHT).
</P>
<P>
Today's talks are seen as crucial as the two sides are likely
to resume deliberations on the repatriation of about 43,000 Chakma
refugees from the Indian state of Tripura and their permanent
settlement in the three hill districts.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation process was stalled after the return of about
7,000 refugees to their homes in the CHT.
</P>
<P>
An official source said that although a peace agreement was not
likely to be reached this time, the meeting would take final
decisions on all unresolved issues including land and the status
of the Muslim settlers.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting is likely to fix a date for signing an agreement
resolving all the issues," said an official of the National
Committee on CHT.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chief Whip and Chairman Abul Hasnat Abdullah and
tribal leader Bodipriya Larma will lead their respective teams to
the sixth round of official talks today.
</P>
<P>
The fifth round was held in mid-July in Dhaka without any
tangible outcome.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, It is reported that a tense situation is prevailing
between the supporters of peace negotiators and their rivals, who
have been demanding self-rule in the resource-rich hill districts
since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
District administration sources said a clash between the
pro-negotiation group and the hard-liner students and youths could
erupt any time. Last week, there were several clashes between the
two sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
