<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Farmers Spend 25.45 M Dollars for Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Regular pest attacks on
croplands have forced Bangladeshi farmers to spend 1.12 billion
taka (about 25.45 million U.S. dollars) annually for buying
pesticides, mainly in rice farming, local press reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
This is an added burden to the hard-bitten farmers who struggle
every year against the imbalance caused by high prices of
agri-inputs and low prices of produce.
</P>
<P>
The farmers spend on average 775 taka (about 17.60 dollars) per
hectare per crop season for pest control, although they usually
apply less than 50 percent of the prescribed dosage.
</P>
<P>
Rice is the most pest-affected crop in the country and about 20
percent of rice is damaged every year by pests like stem borers,
leaf rollers and rice bugs.
</P>
<P>
These pests are usually controlled by chemical insecticides
which cover only 10-20 percent of the cropland in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is an agriculture-based country with over 80 percent
of its 120 million people living in the rural areas. About 50
percent of the population are living below the poverty line and
the percentage in the rural areas is still higher.
</P>
<P>
The country produced 20.34 million tons of grain during
1996-97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Starts Work on Space Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- In its bid to bring to
reality the revolutionary aviation concept of a space plane, the
Indian Institute of Science (IIS) would shortly begin experiments
for developing an in-flight oxygen separator for the "hyperplane,"
a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The experiments, on a ground system of vortex tubes set up as a
technology demonstrator by the Central Cryogenic Facility (CCF) at
the IIS, aims to separate liquid oxygen from liquefied air to be
used as fuel for the hyperplane. It is expected to be completed in
time for a meeting on October 9, the Indian Express quoted IIS
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The hyperplane was conceived by the Defense Research and
Development Organization (DRDO), which envisages a high speed
"single-stage to orbit launch vehicle" that will not only leave
the atmosphere, but also be able to come back to the Earth. The
CCF project is a technology demonstrator for the principle behind
an "air-breathing engine," the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
