<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, Slovenia to Start Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Prime ministers of Bulgaria and
Slovenia have agreed to accelerate talks over Bulgaria's entry
into the Central Europe Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA).
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov met with his Slovenian
counterpart Janez Drnovsek when attending a meeting of prime
ministers of CEFTA member countries on September 12-13 in Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed to hold talks later this month
on trade liberalization of farm produce, the avoidance of double
taxation and mutual protection of investment, the Bulgarian
Telegraph Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Similar negotiations between Bulgaria and Romania are expected
to be held here in October, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria applied in April this year for its entry into CEFTA,
which was established in 1992 by Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic, in a bid to build a free trade zone in Central Europe
before the year of 2002. Slovakia, Slovenia and Romania joined the
CEFTA later.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria has signed an agreement on the establishment of a free
trade zone with the Czech Republic, Slovakia and Slovenia. It will
sign similar accords with Poland and Hungary soon, the report
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
