<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur, EU to Sign Free Trade Accord in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A free trade agreement
will be signed by the European Union (EU) and Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) in 1999, the first region-to-region free trade
accord, European Commission (EC) Vice President Manuel Marin said.
</P>
<P>
Marin made the remarks at the end of the Mercosur Economic
Summit in Sao Paulo on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Marin said that the agreement will be signed during the first
Latin American-European Union Summit, expected to be held during
the first half of 1999 in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
The economic relations between EU and Latin American countries
have been closer and closer. The EC vice president said that the
Mercosur, the South America's largest and most important trade
bloc, has absorbed 70 percent of EU investment in the American
region. Marin said the trade volume between the two organizations
amounted to 50 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be the last of a two-stage process that
began December 1995 when the two regions signed a political and
economic cooperation accord in Madrid. The two blocs also proposed
to establish a free trade area, the largest one in the world,
before 2005.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur summit, the third of its kind since 1995, was
organized by the Geneva-based World Economic Forum and attended by
some 400 business leaders from five continents.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur groups Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay,
with Chile and Bolivia being its associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
