<HEADLINE> Council to Promote Sri Lanka-Singapore Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lanka-Singapore
business council has been set up to facilitate economic ties
between the two countries, the Ceylon Chamber of Commerce said
today.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the council is to promote trade, investment,
joint ventures, tourism and services between Sri Lanka and
Singapore, the chamber said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's exports to Singapore in 1996 stood at three billion
rupees (about 50 million U.S. dollars), a decline of 17.2 percent
compared with 3.6 billion rupees (60.5 million dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sri Lanka's imports from Singapore registered a
record increase of 11.6 percent, rising from 12.8 billion rupees
(217 million dollars) in 1995 to 14.3 billion rupees (242 million
dollars) last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
