<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 14)-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 14 (Xinhua) -- (At Xinhua's request, some
delegates to the ongoing 15th National Congress of the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) write what they see, discuss and think
during the congress in the form of diary, which we think will
provide outsiders with some information about this major event.
The following diary, the third of its kind, was written by Xiong
Lei, senior editor of Xinhua News Agency. -- Editor)
</P>
<P>
When I received a copy of the report to be delivered by Comrade
Jiang Zemin minutes before the opening session of the 15th
National Party Congress on September 12, I was anxious to quickly
read it through. My curiosity prompted me to see where the
difference lies between the draft for soliciting opinions which I
read in July and the finalized version.
</P>
<P>
What moved me is that the suggestions by congress delegates
including me have been absorbed in the final version of the
report.
</P>
<P>
When I handed in my suggestions at that time, I guessed the
ideas by a small potato like me at the grassroots level would not
be taken into consideration. However, I was delighted and inspired
by the result.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the report to the 15th National Party
Congress has been revised for many times. Besides soliciting views
within the Party, the CPC Central Committee also held discussions
to listen to views from the non-Communist parties, leaders of the
All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce and people with no
party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
All those who were asked for comments on the draft of the
report are of the opinion that the report was clear-cut and
hitting the point with new breakthroughs in theory. Meanwhile,
they also earnestly put forward many suggestions for improvements.
</P>
<P>
Before the congress, I and another congress delegate were
invited to a discussion by some young people from the organization
where I work. At the discussion, the young people expressed their
hope that the Party congress will serve as an example for
democracy. When I was asked for suggestions on the report, I
really felt a high-level inner-Party democracy, and such feeling
has augmented as the congress is proceeding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary of Party Congress Delegates (Sept. 14)-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I have been discussing the report by Jiang Zemin together with
many leading officials from different central government
ministries, renowned scholars and highly acclaimed elder comrades.
Many of them joined the Party when I was a kid.
</P>
<P>
However, we have enjoyed equality in discussions and exchanging
views irrespective of differences in ages and official rankings.
In such atmosphere, one cannot but feel exalted with broadened
vision.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin has expounded socialist democracy in his report. On
improving the system of democracy, Jiang Zemin said,"We shall
gradually establish a mechanism that will help the decision-makers
to go deep among the people to see their condition, adequately
reflect their will and pool their wisdom so that decision-making
will be more scientific, democratic and efficient and will reach a
higher level."
</P>
<P>
The remarks by Jiang mean that the CPC Central Committee has
attached great importance to developing democracy. The process of
preparing the report to the Party congress is a process to "go
deep among the people to see their condition, adequately reflect
their will and pool their wisdom."
</P>
<P>
After so many times of discussion and revision, the draft of
Jiang's report was considered excellent and congress delegates and
non-congress delegates spoke highly of the draft. However, it was
again submitted to congress delegates for comments and suggestions
before the report was finalized. This has reflected the CPC
Central Committee's respect for the democratic rights of Party
members.
</P>
<P>
Now the question for us is what kind of altitude we should take
toward democratic rights. If we are afraid of submitting our
proposals or giving out our suggestions only because we are just
small potatoes, we would give up our democratic rights. On the
other hand, it is misunderstanding of democracy if we hold that
100 percent of our proposals should be accepted and that otherwise
democracy would be "suppressed." It is by no means democratic if we
hold that one person's view can overweight 99 persons' views.
</P>
<P>
However, we must acknowledge that our democratic system is yet
to be improved. And therefore the report by Jiang Zemin to
congress stresses improving democratic system. If we all Party
members treasure our democratic rights while respecting the
majority's views and if each individual Party organization at
various levels can act according to the requirements set in the
report, we are really developing democracy.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Party congress has given me a chance to
experience high-level democratic life in the Party, which will be
unforgetable for me. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
