<HEADLINE> Pivotals Remain Subdued on BSE Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Pivotals generally remained
subdued on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market last week mainly
due to the absence of aggressive buying by financial institutions
coupled with lack of local support.
</P>
<P>
The trading for the week began on a better note and share
prices led by Software and Pharma rallied, pushing the sensitive
index to over the 4,100 mark.
</P>
<P>
A few scrips finished with small gains while others closed with
small to modest losses. The volume of business remained below
normal.
</P>
<P>
The sensitive index on the BSE market improved from the
previous week level of 4,032.35 to 4,112.48 but dropped thereafter
to finish at 3,995.94 with the modest loss of 36.41 points. The
national index lost 14.80 points to 1,740.60 from the previous
week level of 1755.40.
</P>
<P>
The trading sentiment was affected considerably during the week
due to the weak trend in rupee against the US dollar. The
unfavorable statement by Finance Minister P. Chidambaram that the
country's fiscal deficit might overshoot the target of 4.5 percent
of the gross domestic product in 1997-98 had an adverse impact on
the market sentiment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
