<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Military Seeks Civilian Help in Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Air Force is
seeking help from a civilian airline company in transporting
troops and supplies to and from Jaffna peninsula and other war
areas in the north and east of the country, local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force finds it difficult to meet the transportation
needs on its own, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted reliable sources as saying that there were
only four aircraft for the military to airlift troops and police
between Jaffna and Colombo, the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The military has therefore asked for help from the Lionair
Group, jointly owned by a Tamil businessman and a former air force
commander and which is the only domestic airline service permitted
to operate after the government banned all domestic airlines for
security purposes.
</P>
<P>
The military has to pay up to 3,000 U.S. dollars a day for the
transport service.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Lionair, the government also has to pay shipping
agencies large sums of money for transporting materiel and troops
between the war areas and Colombo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
