<HEADLINE> Russians Take Last Golds in Roman-Greco Wrestling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 13 (Xinhua) -- The Russian wrestlers took the
last two out of four gold medals at stake as the World Roman-Greco
Wrestling Championships concluded in Wroclaw on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Siergiej Cwir and Aleksander Karelin outwitted their opponents
to award Russia the gold medals in the 85-kg and 130-kg categories
as the four-day competitions ran to the end.
</P>
<P>
The other gold medals of the day were split by Kazakhstan and
South Korea. Jurij Melniczenko won Kazakhstan's first gold in the
58-kg class, while Son Song-Pil won the first for South Korea in
the 69-kg category.
</P>
<P>
Russia finished atop the medal tally with three golds and three
silvers, followed by Turkey with two golds and one silver, as the
trio of Finland, Kazakhstan and South Korea had one gold apiece.
</P>
<P>
In the overall team rankings, Russia again stole the limelight
with 60 points, followed by Turkey 38 and Germany 31. 
</P>
