<HEADLINE> Tung Returns to HK from US Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa returned
here this morning after concluding his first official visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
During the well-knit visit, Tung met with U.S. President Bill
Clinton, leading political figures, business leaders and prominent
think-tanks.
</P>
<P>
"We talked on a whole range of issues and they all
congratulated us on the return of Hong Kong to China and how
smooth everything has been since," Tung told a press conference at
the airport.
</P>
<P>
On some people's concern about next year's first Legislative
Council election, Tung said: "I assured them that we in Hong Kong
are just as much committed to democracy and that we will have a
very fair and open election next year and that we have mapped out
through the Basic Law the political evolution over the next 10
years."
</P>
<P>
There are people (in the U.S.) who understand and support the
election, Tung said. However, "There are some group of people who
just would not support us."
</P>
<P>
"But the important thing is to remember that I did not go there
to ask for their agreement or approval. This is Hong Kong's own
business. It is our own responsibility... We in Hong Kong and Hong
Kong alone can take this decision."
</P>
<P>
Like his first overseas mission as head of post-handover Hong
Kong, which took him to Malaysia and Singapore earlier this month,
the U.S. tour was aimed at explaining that Hong Kong is in good
shape after July 1, while at the same time enhancing the economic
and trade relations between the two trading partners.  
</P>
