<HEADLINE> Carl Lewis Bids Farewell to Atheletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Athletic King Carl Lewis
run his last dash on home turf to bid farewell to the sport of
athletics at the University of Houston on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, the nine-time Olympic champion, run an exhibition 4x100m
relay with three teammates of the Santa Monica Track Club before
thousands of enthusiastic fans.
</P>
<P>
Then, the USA Track and Field retired a symbolic national team
jersey to mark the end of the 36-year-old athlete' competitive
career.
</P>
<P>
Joining in the relay were Leroy Burrell, Mike Marsh and Floyd
Heard, current world record holders in the 4x200m relay.
</P>
<P>
Lewis was a member of five U.S. Olympic teams, winning four
gold medals at the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles and capping his
career with a record-tying ninth Olympic gold medal in the long
jump at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
He trained at the University of Houston for the past 18 years.
He said he will continue to work out with teammates preparing for
the 2000 Olympic games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
