<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Peace Talks Still in Dark as IRA Refuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 13 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair attempted to bring the loyalist parties back to next week's
all-party peace talks on Northern Ireland's future by pledging to
eject Sinn Fein if the IRA broke its cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The IRA attempted to demolish the foundations of the talk on
Thursday by rejecting the Mitchell principles of democracy and
non-violence and vowing to maintain its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the eve of today's crucial Ulster Unionist Party's
(UUP) executive meeting, Tony Blair said that Sinn Fein and the
IRA were inextricably linked and that, if the republicans breached
the Mitchell principles, "they will be out of the talks".
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister also declared that "there must be no change
in the constitutional status of Northern Ireland without the
consent of the majority of people in Northern Ireland".
</P>
<P>
Blair said that he desperately wanted the Unionists to join the
talks. It is now widely expected that the UUP executive will opt
to stay, while opposing face-to-face talks with Sinn Fein, and
will give David Trimble, the party leader, flexibility to proceed
as he sees fit.
</P>
<P>
UUP officials said they believed that the IRA interview in An
Phoblacht, Republican News, was a ploy to provoke a Unionist
boycott, but insisted that the party would not fall into that
trap.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein was similarly unimpressed. Michael Brown, its prisons
spokesman, said "Any measures which improve the conditions of
prisoners have to be welcomed." But the measures were extremely
limited.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, insisted that he wanted
inclusive talks, and urged Unionist leaders to join Sinn Fein at
the talks next week.
</P>
<P>
However, Adams said he signed the Mitchell principles on behalf
of Sinn Fein alone, and again claimed that the IRA was a separate
organization.
</P>
<P>
At this circumstances, some observers here believe that none of
the five Unionist and loyalist parties is likely to be at the
negotiating table next week.
</P>
<P>
After 18 months of division, there are now signs that Unionists
are uniting in opposition to what they see as a process weighted
against the majority population in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovenian, Croatian Premiers Satisfied with Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Both Slovenian Prime Minister
Janez Drnovsek and his Croatian counterpart Zlatko Matesa voiced
satisfaction over their one-hour meeting in Slovenia today.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the meeting in the Slovenian town of Portoroz
where the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) member
states are holding a two-day conference, Matesa said they
discussed the Krsko nuclear plant, the establishment of a free
trade zone and the entire border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian premier expressed optimism about the fact that
some of the questions would be very soon solved and the remaining
ones would not hinder the development of overall bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Drnovsek said he was also optimistic. During the talks he and
Matesa tries to seek rational and pragmatic solutions to the
issues and an agreement on the Krsko power plant could soon be
reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Newspapers Have Bright Future: Media Barons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- Well-written and well-edited
newspapers have a bright future despite a war from Internet,
media barons said.
</P>
<P>
Computer screens are useful, but "reading casually what is
scrolled across a screen for more than a few minutes is
unspeakably irritating", Canada's Conrad Black was quoted as
saying by local media today.
</P>
<P>
"Have any of those who have been most vocal in tolling the
death knell of the printed word ever tried to read lengthily off a
screen? I suspect not," he told a recent meeting in Calgary on the
future of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Tabloid newspapers, which are read for entertainment more than
news, may be vulnerable to electronic competition, but newspapers
read for information may be treated differently, he said.
</P>
<P>
If the content is good, the means of publication is secondary,
Black stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, Black said, newspaper companies will have to adapt to
changing public tastes.
</P>
<P>
Dean Singleton, president of MediaNews Group of the United
States, noted that despite falling circulation in the 1980s,
newspaper readership remains high and newspapers still have the
lion's share of the advertising budget in most markets.
</P>
<P>
It is still difficult for any industry to make money on the
Internet, Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
Internet advertising will account for about 300 million U.S.
dollars in the United States this year, while newspaper
advertising is expected to approach 45 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: British Monarchy Questioned in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 13 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian cabinet minister
has broken the silence and openly called for an end to the British
queen's role as head of state in the country.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister John Manley said he favors a radical change
to Canada's constitutional landscape, including abolishing the
senate and ending the monarchy's role in Canadian affairs.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't soon engage the discussion, the British will have
done away with the monarchy before Canadians do," Manley is
reported to have told a Vancouver newspaper this week.
</P>
<P>
"My own personal view is that it's probably time for us to
say,`It's been a great institution.' Perhaps on the death or
demise of the incumbent queen, maybe we should have a new
institution that maybe reflects Canada's priorities."
</P>
<P>
As the new millennium approaches, "surely it's time we took on
some vision of the future," the minister suggested.
</P>
<P>
With the remarks, Manley became the first cabinet minister to
make his personal views known on the future of the royal family in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Today's local reports suggested that Manley uncorked the
long-bottled debate about the monarchy after he sought and
received approval from Prime Minister Jean Chretien's office.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that the ruling Liberal Party of Canada is
testing the waters, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy told
reporters last week that he would welcome a debate on the
monarchy's role in Canada when he went to London to attend Prince
Diana's funeral.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Prime Minister Chretien office denied that the Liberal
government has any intention of engaging in another constitutional
debate.
</P>
<P>
"We have enough on our plate," said chief spokesman Peter
Donolo. "It's not an issue in Quebec any more. It was an issue
there 30 years ago, but it hasn't really been since then."
</P>
<P>
However, the issue could be in a position to help Canada's
national unity. Ending Canada's ties with the British monarchy
would sell well in Quebec, some argued.
</P>
<P>
A poll conducted last year found that 67 percent of Quebecers
favored the abolition of Canada's connection with the British
queen.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, 47 percent wanted the ties ended while 44
percent wanted it preserved.
</P>
<P>
Liberal MP Mick Discepola of Quebec said he would take part in
a debate on the monarchy if there is evidence it could advance the
cause of national unity.
</P>
<P>
Bloc Quebecois MP Claude Bachand, the party's citizenship
critic, said he was "quite delighted" by Manley's comments.
</P>
<P>
The monarchy is "something of the past and it should be
changed," he said. "The powers should be in the hands of the
people who are elected in Canada or in the provinces."
</P>
<P>
Yet, Reform MP Jim Abbott of British Columbia is less
enthusiastic about the debate.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have been far too ready in Canada to throw away our
heritage," he said. "The monarchy, in my judgement, is a very
important part of our Canadian heritage and who we are."
</P>
<P>
Manley's views encountered the strongest criticism from the
Monarchist League of Canada, which claims 17,000 members.
</P>
<P>
"It's not helpful to have ministers of the Crown to suggest
such fundamental change in our constitution when we are not able
to agree on the status of Quebec," said the league's chairman John
Aimers.
</P>
<P>
"To include the monarchy in the national debate at this point
would seem both irresponsible and contrary to the wishes of
Canadians," he argued.
</P>
<P>
Yet, there is an example for Canada to follow. Australia, a
constitutional monarchy like Canada, is now in the midst of its
own monarchy debate.
</P>
<P>
The South Pacific country will hold a convention early next
year to decide whether to drop its association with the British
queen.
</P>
<P>
A slight majority of Australians believe that the country
should become a republic with an Australian head of state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970914.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-14 </DATE_TIME>
